title: Monoprice MP Select Mini V1 Z-axis Bearing Pillow

description.text:
This is another step in my attempt to stabilize the z-axis rod in my MP Mini. After I replaced the tin can stepper with a small nema17 model, I decided to try a laterally-flexible coupler and dual 608 skateboard bearing pillow to center the rod and move the possibly bent portion higher up the travel to minimize lateral movement for at least the lower portion of the print. It screws into the two holes left by the tin can stepper, The flat spot is to allow it clearance for the right-side z-axis smooth rod base.

The pillow block takes a pair of 608 bearings stacked on top of each other. The fit is quite tight, so you have have to run some sandpaper around the inside to smooth out the ridges and allow pressing them in. The spacer is for an m5 rod. I heated an m5 bolt and screwed it in to establish threads, but you could either tap threads in it, or drill it out to just slip the spacer over the rod. I used a brass m5 nut on the top and bottom of the bearings, but I am not sure that is necessary.

The coupler is just a length of silicone tubing with an airsoft bb between the stepper shaft and z-axis screw to keep it vertically-stable, but allow rocking and lateral movement.

That is, assuming the shaft and screw line up (my stepper isolated onto a plate that I can align manually).

description.text:
"Ježek v kleci" (hedgehog in the cage) is a puzzle very popular in Czech Republic and some other countries because of famous set of adventure books where it's the main artifact everyone is looking for. EN Wikipedia, CZ Wikipedia

Scaling of holes and spines was inspired by official model for Hedgehog-freeing World's Championship.

Size: 47x47x85 mm (cage)

Challenge: The best time to free the hedgehog (with prepared hedgehog and cage, so it isn't a competition attempt) is 3 seconds (!!!) (no, it's not me). See video here.

Prusa

Prusa Mk2

0.2

20%

Notes:

Use supports just for the cage! Hedgehog halves shouldn't need any.

File jezek-model.stl is not for printing, it's just a demo!

Assembling the Hedgehog

Original Hedgehog from book was hollow and screwable. Nowadays most of them are solid - its more durable and spines are still in correct position (in other positions there is chance the puzzle won't have any solution).

You can choose one of 2 possible versions:

  1. solid: There are three 1.8mm holes which allows you to connect the halves just by three pieces of filament. The holes are not placed regularly so its impossible to assemble it to the state with no solution. You can glue the halves together, or just let it be like this and use the inner hollow.
  2. screwable (needs support): Use hollow screw rod (thanks to NUTJOB) to screw halves together. Inner space is a cylinder with diameter 10mm and height 13mm. edit: 19.8.2017 tested and works fine
    You may have troubles printing screwable hedgehog - then consider to use "jezek-rafts" model.

title: Monoprice MP Mini V1 floating z-axis leadscrew nut adapter

description.text:
Yet another experiment in ridding my printer of z-banding. This model takes a long m5 coupling nut -- since I changed my rod from m4 to m5 -- which presses in (I secured mine with epoxy just out of paranoia). The nut can float from side to side. 4-40 or 3mm machine screws are secured by a pair of nuts each. The whole x-axis assembly rests on top of this leadnut and is held in place by gravity. You could use a pair of nuts locked against each other on the bottom of each leg as well if you have stiction in your z-axis movement when traveling downward.

I included 2 and 4 leg versions. Both seem to work similarly well, but the 2-leg version has more float (but possibly more backlash).

I am currently using this setup on my printer, and it seems to work for me in conjunction with my bearing pillow http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2304205 and a flexible coupler.

title: APC UPS Battery Divider (for SMART UPS battery modules)

description.text:
This is an incredibly simple design that replaces the battery divider in larger APC UPS battery banks. The full battery module is comprised of several smaller lead acid batteries, each battery is seperated by one of these small dividers to keep the batteries from touching each other. This is handy when batteries start expanding.

The APC battery modules come with these preinstalled, but they are easily broken when removing swollen batteries from a defective module. Hence why I'm uploading this design.

APC modules that use these are usually in the Smart UPS series (4000, 5000, 6000, etc)

description.text: This thing is what I used to add to my homemade spiderman suit when I needed a logo. It can be used front and back, and is flat.

General purpose Kobalt power tool battery adapter. I use copper pipe hangers to make the terminal plates. I use screw inserts and 6-32 screws as the screw terminals. The batteries are well priced at Lowes. I regularly see the Li-ion 1.5Ah 24v battery for $10, and the 2.0Ah 24v battery for $20. They also have a charger for $39. When comparing to all the hassle of RC LiPo batteries, these are way easier to unplug, charge, and swap out. They also have a battery voltage meter built into each battery.

The battery I've been getting for $10: https://www.lowes.com/pd/Kobalt-24-Volt-1-5-Amp-Hours-Lithium-Power-Tool-Battery/1000090833

The charger: https://www.lowes.com/pd/Kobalt-24-Volt-Max-Power-Tool-Battery-Charger/1000102901

The things I use to make my terminals: https://www.lowes.com/pd/AMERICAN-VALVE-1-2-in-to-1-2-in-dia-Copper-Plated-Steel-Milford-Hanger/3223453

The screw inserts I use to hold the screws (Screw-to_expand inserts for Through Holes in Plastics - 6-32): https://www.mcmaster.com/#catalog/123/3328/=17jdfht

WARNING - don't allow the terminals on the bottom side to ground across whatever you mount this to. Insulate them. I haven't see what happens when you short out a 24v Li-Ion battery, and I don't want to see it.

I usually print this with PETG. I don't recommend printing it with PLA unless you make the base thicker. It really could be a tad thicker in PETG too.

I print it upside down from what the STL that's I've uploaded reflects. I add supports to the inside overhangs, and to the bottom side notching for the terminals.

I designed this in FreeCad, and I have also attached the FreeCad source file if anyone wants to edit the source objects.

If you'd like a more snug fit, or you want to adapt it to a size other than 1/4" hex, just scale the whole model up appropriately -- remember, Quadrant Drive doesn't care how big it is, it will mate just fine with any other Quadrant Drive.

The Thyssen-Krupp Stairlift is a very useful thing but if you want the lift coming down two levels you must hold down the switch for more than two and a half minute. For me this was so annoying that I made a tool for adding a HOLD-function to that switch. The waiting time remains but it is no longer necessary to hold your finger on the switchknob all the time.
Once the lift has arrived you have to release the switchshifter. Forgetting this can empty the battery stored in the switch. For the liftoperation itself there is no problem because the the operating switch on the seat is overruling the wall-mounted switch.
Be aware that a holding device as described here is NOT recommended by Thyssen-Krupp: that is for safety reasons. Mounting and using this switchholder is your own responsibility.
The actual latch is consisting of two parts which are glued together with superglu.
Print the parts, remove flash and clean them. The switch housing is removed from the wall by removing the inner batteryholder and remove the 2 screws. Remount the housing as shown in the picture. The so called switchkey can simply be pulled out; the printed knob can be clamped on that key whereafter the key can be pushed back into the wall-mounted device.

Tetrarhons are four rhombic dodecahedrons joined at their faces. Among the 28 pieces there are 14 planar ones with all four parts touching a plane. Nine pieces can be used only in a hexagonal lattice, four pieces only in a square lattice and the straight one in both lattices. With all pieces 3-dimensional constructions are possible.

In my program the rhombic dodecahedrons were represented by cubes in a cubic lattice. Therefore I must turn the pieces around to get at least one rhomb in the x-y-plane. Then I printed the pieces with ABS-filament (0.4mm nozzle) and removed the support material. Since the faces got an inset of 0.2mm little differences in size doesn't matter that much.

The comic strip Calvin and Hobbes follows the humorous antics of Calvin, a precocious, mischievous and adventurous six-year-old boy, and Hobbes, his sardonic stuffed tiger.

Printing and assembly tips

1-No supports are required.
..
2-The stripes are designed to be a single layer thickness of .2mm, or less as long as they print solid on your machine.
..
3-Be sure to clean any first layer squish if you have any problem joining parts. The parts should fit nicely when printed cleanly.
..
Assembly tips:
-'Stripes! There had to be stripes!' I avoided creating this model for quite some time due to the stripes. I finally settled on a design:
. The stripes are printed flat, one layer high
. The parts that the stripes are glued to contain indents for stripe placement.
. Most of the stripes are slightly curved to help wrap around the surface.
-*Important: To make it simpler to glue flat stripes to a round surface, take a moment to curl the stripes like you would with a piece of ribbon. Using a flat edge, pull the stripe along the edge to make it curl. Pay special attention to the very ends and ensure the ends curl.
-Test the length of each stripe before gluing, due to printer differences, stripes may need to be trimmed a bit.
-Optionally, instead of using the 3D printed stripes, the stripes can be painted on using the indents as a guide.
-The diagram below will help in assembling the model and is quite straightforward.
-The model is meant to be glued together. I use E6000 glue. It is a nice clear tacky glue allowing for easy part positioning. The longer you let it sit before joining parts, especially for the stripes, the tackier it gets until it fully sets.
-The Calvin model fits the log using the Thingiverse links provided in the introduction.

description.text:
Just another Fidget Spinner which uses 5 Euro-Cent coins (4x for each arm).
It is a little bit bigger in diameter and heavyer than using 608Z bearings (72.3g instead of 54.8g)
I recommend the caps from 2ROBOTGUY's design: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1802260
The Coins are nestled inside the spinner, so you have to pause the print right before the first top solid layer begins (0.4mm before end). If you are using 0.2mm layer resolution you have to stop between layer 36 and 37.
In Simplify 3D you can use the post processing command. For my Prusa I3 clone (Anet A8) the code looks like this;

{STRIP "; postProcessing,"}
{REPLACE "; layer 37," "G91 G1 Z10 G90 G1 X0 Y200 M0 Click To Restart G91 G1Z-10 G90 ; layer 37,"}

I bought some time ago a DDS Signal Generator in a Chinese web shop. I was cheap but had no housing or case. In order not to damage the device, I decided to make one myself.

I have drawn first the generator, so I could use this model to shape the box around the device. The 6 buttons were a bit tricky to design, but I worked out fine. I used 3mm Plexiglass, PMMA. You need 3 mm thick material else the buttons won't fit and are to lose. The case is closed and held together with long m3 x 40 mm screw and nuts. But any screw m3 longer than 33 mm is long enough. The PCB of the generator is also set with M3 screws and nut. Anything longer than 10 mm will do.

I've used SolidWorks to draw this box. I added a dxf-file so it can be imported in most laser cutter software.

description.text:
Yet another fidget spinner. This on based on the suggestions and process from Joel, AKA the "3D Printing Nerd" as found here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EgOuvOLiwAM

The fit is very snug so the pennies won't fall out. I had to use a bit of force to get the pennies in. It may be just my printer (calibration prints measured to be about .1-.5% over size) but you may need to up-scale a few percent for easy assembly.

The caps are "monogrammed" but I have also uploaded blank ones if you don't share the initial.

Print, smash in a bearing, 15 pennies, and the caps. Enjoy!

(Drop me a note for the Fusion360 files if you want them)

Update: Printed one out in Ninjaflex for fun. Much more durable but the pennies need to be glued in place...

(Technically printed on a Printrbot Metal Plus but its not in the list)
I used 3 top and 3 bottom layers, 2 shells (wall). Fillets are small enough to not need support. Printed directly on bed, no raft.

Money, money, money...

Caps may not come apart easily. Be prepared to replace them if you try to take spinner apart.

description.text:
UK plug and cable tidy block - great for like-minded hoarders who just can't part with an old cable or mains adapter.

Designed to be screwed to something solid, the block provides space for 7 UK plugs of nearly all sizes or a combination of UK plugs and assorted cables using the 'Fork of Support' which can hold up to 10 LAN cables each. Both block and plugs can be orientated so cables always hang freely. Easy access and organisation guaranteed.

The block measures 239mm wide, 70mm high and 25mm deep. The forks protrude 39mm from the block face when fully inserted.

title: BW 05 02 09 Aifoil Micro Drone Propeller (26,97g thrust @ 3V)

description.text:
This micro drone propeller has been designed after the BW 05 02 09 airfoil. It was tested on the Drone Propeller Thrust Tester The results can be seen below.

It was printed slowly, using a 0.2mm nozzle at 0.04 height per layer. The print was cleaned using an X-ACTO Knife

After this, it was sanded with a small piece of 500 grit sandpaper.

These are the thrust readings for some voltage values (you can also check these out in the images):

  • 1.5V => 12.44 grams
  • 2V => 17.19 grams
  • 2.5V => 22.08 grams
  • 3V => 26.97 grams

The files I included contain all shots taken during the test, with 6 text files that have all the airfoil coordinates used in the build, the STL files and the SLDPRT files. Should you want to print this propeller, you should grab a 8520 coreless motor.

You should use the SLDPRT files, in case you wish to adapt the propeller model to suit your own needs.

Note: Airfoil plotted by using the matplotlib library in python.

description.text:
This is a triple-decker functioning fidget spinner. It is absurd, of course, but fun to make.

The key print is the connector, which snaps together two bearings that are each a part of an individual fidget spinner. The spacer is needed between them to keep them from banging into each other. I have included three different spinners, one with Triple Lindy Spinner written on it, one with no text, and another that is slightly smaller. Having the two different sizes can make a nice effect when spinning. The connected spinners can go in the same or in opposite directions.

To make the third (optional) layer, add three of the "miniSpinners," which each use only one bearing and are small enough that they won't collide with each other when attached to the outer bearings of the main spinner.

I'll leave at an exercise to the reader to figure out how to make this a quadruple spinner (hint, it's very easy).

Everything is designed for standard 608ZZ bearings. You can mix and match parts creatively. To make the triple lindy in the picture, you need 11 bearings. You then need to print 4 connectors, 4 spacers, three miniSpinners, one regular spinner (with or without the text) and one spinnerSmaller. The minSpinners make it difficult to hold and still spin everything, so it is best to put it on a table as shown in the first picture, then everything can be set in motion.

If you want your own customized spinner with text, try my Custom Captioned Fidget Spinner (Dual Extrusion)

(Named after the most amazing dive I saw down at the Steel Pier in Jersey).

To simply connect two spinners and make a double-decker, just pass the connector through one, add a spacer, then pass through the second spinner.

To make the full triple lindy, it's basically the same process times four. Generally the assembly is best if the flat end of the connector holding the two full spinners is on the opposite side of the three mini-spinners.
All designed on openscad. Will hopefully have a post-able version of the .scad files soon.
